    contentHeader: "Blazers & Sustainability",
    content:
      "<p class='first'>It’s September and the first rains are here, along with the start of a new semester (that is if you are a student, of course). The one thing I noticed as soon as I came back to University this year was that oversized blazers for women are back!</p><p>During my first lectures I still styled myself in a bachelor-y manner: flared jeans, t-shirt and trainers. But, now, the mood has changed.</p><p>I don’t like to describe myself as someone who strictly follows trends – nor as a feminist - but I love how girls this first graduate year are just going all in with the smart look: (blue light) glasses, pastel shirts and autumn-coloured blazers. It was a coup de foudre. </p><p>Blazers were really popular in the 90s among youth. However, growing up in catholic schools, I was only required to wear them on important and serious occasions, such as communion and masses. Since then I remember having a rather troubled relationship with blazers, and I did not believe I could ever wear – or even like – them again. </p><p>Today, my opinion has completely shifted and I consider blazers to be a wardrobe basic, a must have, and a go-to item. It is the perfect garment to wear for university lectures, to the office, for a virtual meeting or for an in-person conference. To sum up, blazers are the ideal clothing piece for (lightly) serious events or for an everyday casual fit. </p><div class='grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-x-2 '><div class='w-[200px]  m-auto sm:w-[400px]  sm:h-[500px]'><img src='/images/blazers-1.jpg' class='object-cover h-full w-full py-2 sm:py-0' /></div><div class='w-[200px] m-auto  sm:w-[400px] sm:h-[500px]'><img src='/images/blazers-2.jpg' class=' object-cover h-full w-full py-2 sm:py-0' /></div></div><div class='sm:py-8 flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center justify-center'><img src='/images/blazers-3.jpg' class='sm:pr-5 object-cover  w-full sm:w-[300px] h-[350px] py-2 sm:py-0'/><div><p>As soon as I noticed this trend, I immediately fell in lovewith it. I knew I had to find my own way to express myselfthrough a blazer and to let my university fashion style shine.I started digging into my closet and I found a V-neck sweatervest that could have easily been styled with a white blouseshirt and Harry Styles wide-legged sailor-style trousers.</p><p>Despite the latter very appealing choice, I was determined to dig deeper to find THE blazer. And that’s when I thought of the perfect place to look for it: my mom’s wardrobe (a vintage market will do too)! An enormous amount of perfectly stored blazers popped up, each with a different colour and pattern. </p></div></div><div class='flex flex-col md:flex-row items-center'><p><div>During these first few weeks of lectures, in my Marketing course, we explored the concept of how consumers with a fixed budget have a tendency to prefer quantity over quality in terms of fashion items. </p><p>My mom’s blazer was from MaxMara, a notorious high-end brand for jackets. It was bought almost 40 years ago but it looked as if I had bought it the same day. Surely my mom had done a great job at preserving it in her wardrobe, but most of the credit goes to the high quality of the garment. </p><p>A research paper proposed by Sun et al. (2021), concerning luxury designer brands and sustainability, is based on two interesting hypotheses. The first one was that consumers prefer to buy multiple items rather than one luxurious one, given the same budget, and the second one implied consumers’ neglect of durability. In fact, when we come to think about it if we would hold back from giving in into our consumerist self, we would be able to save more and, thereby, afford fewer luxurious clothing pieces, that would last overtime (almost like an investment).</p></div><img src='/images/blazers-4.jpg' class=' object-cover sm:w-[400px] sm:pl-4 '/></div><div class='flex flex-col md:flex-row md:justify-between md:gap-6 sm:py-8'><div class='sm:pr-3 md:w-6/12'><p>The paper was written from a sustainability standpoint. Therefore, buying less but more luxurious items better preserves the environment, in terms of sustainability, as consumers' would stop supporting fast-fashion companies such as Shein. The Chinese company's buying mentality consists in purchasing numerous garments at a low price, which is detrimental to the environment and pushes consumers into buying things that - most of the time - are not truly needed.</p><img src='/images/blazers-5.jpg' class=' object-cover w-full py-2 sm:py-0'/></div><div class='sm:pl-3 md:w-6/12'><img src='/images/blazers-6.jpg' class=' object-cover  w-full py-2 sm:py-0'/><p class='sm:pt-5'>Coming back to my University days, I ended up styling my mom’s blazer - in a sportier, casual yet classy way - with a white shirt from Lacoste, a P&B wide legged light brown jeans and AirForce One white trainers. I then went to class and rocked it! </p></div></div>",
    month: "JAN 2023",
    img: "/images/blazers.jpg",
    author: "Giorgia Candreva",
    topics: ["FASHION & BEAUTY", "COST OF LIVING"],
    theme: "",
    date: "January 01, 2023",
    template: 2,
