    id: 35,
    mainHeader: "Abolishing Acne: From the Inside Out!",
    subHeader: "",
    contentHeader: "Abolishing Acne: From the Inside Out!",
    content:
      "<p class='first'>Acne: the world’s most common skincare struggle. Ways to combat it vary - there are countless products on the market designed to clean the pores and banish blemishes, with varying degrees of success. </p><p>But having an extensive skin care routine isn’t always a viable option in the hectic, busy world we live in, especially with the current cost of living crisis, which is seeing the price of beauty products soar. So here are 5 alternative ways to treat acne from the inside out.</p><h3 class='sub-head'>Hormone Hacks</h3><p>Hormone imbalance is a contributor to the acne issues some people face, especially because of unbalanced oestrogen. Excess oestrogen stimulates oil production, giving rise to clogged pores and flare ups. </p><p>To avoid oestrogen dominance, you can reduce the amount of processed foods you eat, as they often contain high levels of oestrogen. Eating fibrous foods to help excrete excess oestrogen from the body is also an effective way to combat oestrogen over-production.</p><h3 class='sub-head'>A Carrot A Day…</h3><p>Carrots are packed with high levels of vitamin A and beta-carotene (this gives the carrot their orange colour). Both can reduce inflammation of the skin and encourage regular cell turnover (the skin exfoliating itself). </p><p>Additionally, carrots contain lots of fibre, which helps the body excrete excess oestrogen (which, as noted earlier is a common cause of acne). This works because if the bowels don’t move regularly, oestrogen meant to be excreted gets reabsorbed into the bile. Fibre, known for helping bowels stay healthy, is key to keeping oestrogen levels down. Eating a raw carrot daily is said to be the best way to see results quickly.</p><div><img src='/images/abolishingAcne-1.jpg' class='block m-auto h-[400px] object-cover'/><p class='text-sm text-center py-2'>Image Credit: https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/carrot-juice-benefits</p></div><h3 class='sub-head'>Dairy Decrease</h3><p>Dairy products can contain hormones that throw off your body’s natural balance, which as established before can lead to issues with excess oil production. There’s no need to cut dairy out of your diet completely: it’s a good source of vitamin D, which is vital for skin repair, cell growth and protection. But if you’re having issues with acne and have a dairy heavy diet, try reducing the amount for a month and look for changes in your complexion.</p><div><img src='/images/abolishingAcne-2.jpg' class='block m-auto h-[400px] object-cover'/><p class='text-sm text-center py-2'>Image Credit: https://deliciouslysavvy.com/what-to-know-about-cutting-out-dairy/</p></div><h3 class='sub-head'>Balance your blood sugar</h3><p>Insulin (the hormone that reduces your blood sugar levels after eating) can in excess contribute to acne breakouts. This is because it can lead to chronic inflammation, blocking pores and making the skin prone to acne.</p><p>To balance your blood sugar levels, make sure you’re eating plenty of healthy (unprocessed) fats. Fat slows down the absorption of glucose into the bloodstream through insulin and prevents sugar highs and sugar crashes. This reduces insulin levels, preventing it from inflaming the skin.</p><h3 class='sub-head'>Hydrate</h3><p>Drinking plenty of water can improve just about everything, from your mood to your overall health. This goes for acne too, as when your skin is properly hydrated, the pores don’t need to produce excess oil to moisturise the skin. Reducing oil production reduces the risk of your pores getting clogged and forming acne.</p>Acne can seem like an undefeatable issue without being able to navigate the ever growing, ever more costly market of skincare products. But it is possible to have healthy skin through a balanced diet and body.</p><div><img src='/images/abolishingAcne-3.jpg' class='block m-auto h-[400px] object-cover'/><p class='text-sm text-center py-2'>Image Credit: https://sflcn.com/how-to-soften-your-water-in-south-florida/</p></div>",
    img: "/images/abolishingAcne-1.jpg",
    month: "MAR 2023",
    author: "Eve Turner",
    topics: ["FASHION & BEAUTY", "SKIN"],
    theme: "",
    date: "March 01, 2023",
    template: 2,
